{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17531389","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17531389"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T16:14:22+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T16:14:22+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14595"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14595","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14595"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.33,0.2,0.42,0.03,0.03]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7288"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115481"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7288","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7288"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14595"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97484"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"26"},{"type":"tags","id":"32"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"1194"},{"type":"tags","id":"1493"},{"type":"tags","id":"2443"},{"type":"tags","id":"3310"},{"type":"tags","id":"5826"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"17798"},{"type":"contributions","id":"18454"},{"type":"contributions","id":"18460"},{"type":"contributions","id":"49052"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115481","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/115481"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 25-year-old man is admitted to the Intensive Care Unit following a motor vehicle accident. He has a Glasgow Coma Scale score of 6 (E1V1M4). His medical history includes asthma, for which he uses salbutamol as needed. He does not take any other regular medications. On examination, his pulse rate is 88/min, blood pressure 145/85 mmHg, respiratory rate 14/min (ventilated), SpO2 98% on 40% oxygen, and temperature 36.8\u00b0C. His pupils are equal and reactive. A CT brain shows diffuse cerebral oedema with effaced basal cisterns. An intracranial pressure (ICP) monitor has been inserted, showing a pressure of 28 mmHg (5-15 mmHg).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Decompressive craniectomy","Hyperventilation","Hypertonic saline","Increase sedation","Therapeutic hypothermia"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient has severe traumatic brain injury with evidence of raised intracranial pressure (normal ICP is 5-15 mmHg). The immediate goal is to reduce ICP while maintaining adequate cerebral perfusion pressure.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOf the listed options,\u003Cstrong\u003E hypertonic saline\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate first-line treatment for acute elevation in ICP. It creates an osmotic gradient that draws water from the brain tissue into the intravascular space, thereby reducing cerebral oedema - this is known as hyperosmolar therapy and is the mainstay of treatment for elevated ICP. Another hyperosmolar agent which can be used is mannitol - both are appropriate treatments, and whilst different locations may tend to use one or the other, there is no universal guideline and the therapies can be used interchangeably. Therefore, of the options listed, hypertonic saline in the most appropriate next step. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIncreasing sedation\u003C/strong\u003E may help reduce ICP by decreasing cerebral metabolic demand, but it is not the most effective immediate intervention for an acute rise in ICP.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDecompressive craniectomy\u003C/strong\u003E is a surgical intervention reserved for cases refractory to medical management. It would be premature to proceed directly to surgery before trying osmotic therapy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETherapeutic hypothermia\u003C/strong\u003E remains controversial in traumatic brain injury. While it may reduce ICP, it has not been shown to improve outcomes and carries significant risks including coagulopathy and infection.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHyperventilation\u003C/strong\u003E causes cerebral vasoconstriction and can rapidly decrease ICP, but it also reduces cerebral blood flow and may worsen cerebral ischaemia. It should be used only as a temporary measure for acute deterioration while preparing other interventions.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Intracranial pressure monitoring is indicated in patients with severe traumatic brain injury (GCS \u22648) and abnormal CT findings.","The goal of ICP management is to maintain cerebral perfusion pressure above 60 mmHg.","Hyperosmolar therapy with mannitol or hypertonic saline is indicated for acute rises in intracranial pressure."],"references":["Patel, S., Maria-Rios, J., Parikh, A. et al. Diagnosis and management of elevated intracranial pressure in the emergency department. Int J Emerg Med 16, 72 (2023). https://doi.org/10.1186/s12245-023-00540-x","Changa, A.R., Czeisler, B.M. \u0026 Lord, A.S. Management of Elevated Intracranial Pressure: a Review. Curr Neurol Neurosci Rep 19, 99 (2019). https://doi.org/10.1007/s11910-019-1010-3","Gu, J., Huang, H., Huang, Y. et al. Hypertonic saline or mannitol for treating elevated intracranial pressure in traumatic brain injury: a meta-analysis of randomized controlled trials. Neurosurg Rev 42, 499\u2013509 (2019). https://doi.org/10.1007/s10143-018-0991-8"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97484"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14595"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia"